					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On September 13, 2008 at 04:19 AM, Chocoholic (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">I know this probably sounds real stupid, but is it okay to use baking chips? I always read about using bars- does it make a difference?</div>
					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On September 13, 2008 at 10:32 PM, Michael Chu said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>Chocoholic wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>I know this probably sounds real stupid, but is it okay to use baking chips? I always read about using bars- does it make a difference?</div></div><br />
Check the ingredients on your chips. Sometimes they contain paraffin wax and other stabilizers and this can affect how they work. If it's just pure chocolate - cocoa (or cacao) solids, cocoa butter/fat, lecithin (as an emulsifier), and sugar - then you should be in good shape. Any other ingredients and you should probably keep looking for the real thing.</div>
					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On September 18, 2008 at 09:15 PM, Ma Jie (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Truffle Quality Chocolates</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">The best chocolate for truffles is from either Sharffen-Berger, an American chocolatier, or that made by Valhrona in France.  Using any sort of chocolate chips, in my opinion, is not a good idea.  <br />
<br />
In dishes when there are only a few ingredients, you really have to use the best-possible ingredients that you can find because there's nothing for the inferior chocolate to hide behind.  <br />
<br />
- Jie</div>
